03912nam a22006375i 9780292799912DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211995txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927999127 a10.7560/7813372doi  a(DE-B1597)586599  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1565.2.C8T53 1995eb 7aBUS0680002bisacsh04a330.972871 aTice, Karin E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKuna Crafts, Gender, and the Global Economy /cKarin E. Tice. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1995  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Theoretical Framework -- t3. Traveling to San Blas -- t4. Political Economy of San Blas -- t5. Mola Commercialization -- t6. Mola Production, Exchange, and Use -- t7. Kuna Women Organize -- t8. Tourism and Molas on Carti-Sugtupu -- t9. The Mola Cooperative on Tupile -- t10. Molas and Middlemen in Mansucun: A Discussion of Female-supported Households -- t11. Insights from San Blas: Crafts, Gender, and the Global Economy -- tAppendix: Methodology -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Kuna and Spanish Terms -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBrightly colored and intricately designed, molas have become popular with buyers across the United States, Europe, and Japan, many of whom have never heard of the San Blas Kuna of Panama who make the fabric pictures that adorn the clothing, wall hangings, and other goods we buy. In this study, Karin Tice explores the impact of the commercialization of mola production on Kuna society, one of the most important, yet least studied, social changes to occur in San Blas in this century. She argues that far from being a cohesive force, commercialization has resulted in social differentiation between the genders and among Kuna women residing in different parts of the region. She also situates this political economic history within a larger global context of international trade, political intrigue, and ethnic tourism to offer insights concerning commercial craft production that apply far beyond the Kuna case. These findings, based on extensive ethnographic field research, constitute important reading for scholars and students of anthropology, women's studies, and economics. They also offer an indigenous perspective on the twentieth-century version of Columbus's landing—the arrival of a cruise ship bearing wealthy, souvenir-seeking tourists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Economic Development.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799912423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799912/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK